@node PREFIX MARKER and TAG Keywords
@subsubsection PREFIX, MARKER, and TAG Keywords
@cindex MARKER keyword
@cindex PREFIX keyword
@cindex TAG keyword

User-defined prefixes, markers, and tags are optional character strings that
help to uniquely identify the names associated with a particular facility or
system.  When the @command{--suppress} qualifier is specified on the command
line, the inclusion of prefixes and/or tags on output symbol names is
suppressed.  See @ref{Processing an OpenSDL Source File} for a description of
the @command{--suppress} qualifier.
@cindex Command line qualifiers

@subsubheading PREFIX Keyword

The @code{PREFIX} option may be specified on an @code{AGGREGATE}, subaggregate,
@code{CONSTANT}, or @code{ITEM} declaration to cause OpenSDL to concatenate a
user-specified prefix and the name specified in the declaration.
@cindex AGGREGATE keyword
@cindex AGGREGATE declaration
@cindex CONSTANT keyword
@cindex CONSTANT declaration
@cindex ITEM keyword
@cindex ITEM declaration
@cindex PREFIX keyword
@cindex Subaggregate declaration

When you specify a prefix for an aggregate, OpenSDL concatenates the prefix and
the name of each member or named constant declared within the aggregate.  The
name of the aggregate itself is not altered by the use of the @code{PREFIX}
option.  The @code{PREFIX} option has the following syntax:
@cindex AGGREGATE member
@cindex Named constants
@cindex PREFIX keyword

@example
PREFIX prefix-string
@end example

@strong{prefix-string}
@indentedblock
Is a 0 to 32-character string that can be any valid OpenSDL identifier.
If you specify the @code{PREFIX} option, OpenSDL constructs the identifier of
each member by concatenating the prefix, a tag, an underscore, and the member
name.
@end indentedblock

You can override a prefix that is currently in effect by specifying a new
prefix for a particular aggregate member.  If this member happens to be a
subaggregate, the new prefix is applied to all the members of that
subaggregate.  Otherwise, if no prefix is specified for the subaggregate, all
subaggregate members are assigned the same prefix as that specified on the
parent aggregate.
@cindex Subaggregate declaration

@subsubheading MARKER Keyword
@cindex MARKER keyword

You can use the @code{MARKER} keyword to assign a user-defined prefix to the
aggregate name.  The @code{MARKER} option has the following syntax:

@example
MARKER marker-string
@end example

@strong{marker-string}
@indentedblock
Is a 0 to 32-character string that can be any valid OpenSDL name that may or
may not be enclosed in quotation marks (" ") and may be null.
@end indentedblock

@subsubheading TAG Keyword

The @code{TAG} option overrides the default tags that OpenSDL uses in forming
identifiers.  You can specify tags for @code{CONSTANT}, @code{ITEM}, and
@code{AGGREGATE} declarations and aggregate members.  The tag that you specify,
however, affects only the outer-level identifier.  For example, a tag you
supply in an @code{AGGREGATE} declaration affects only the aggregate name; if
you wish to change all the tags in an aggregate, you must do it on a
member-by-member basis.  The @code{TAG} option has the following syntax:
@cindex AGGREGATE keyword
@cindex AGGREGATE declaration
@cindex AGGREGATE member
@cindex CONSTANT keyword
@cindex CONSTANT declaration
@cindex Identifiers, OpenSDL generated
@cindex ITEM keyword
@cindex ITEM declaration
@cindex TAG keyword

@example
TAG tag-string
@end example

@strong{tag-string}
@indentedblock
Is a 0 to 32-character string specifying the tag to use in forming the name.
If the TAG option is not specified, OpenSDL uses a default code based on the
data type of the name.
@end indentedblock
@cindex Data type, tag
@cindex TAG keyword

If you specify the @code{TAG} option, OpenSDL appends the tag-string, which may
be null (" "), and an underscore character (_) to the current prefix-string.  A
tag consisting of a single underscore character produces a single underscore
character in any resulting identifier.
@cindex TAG keyword

The following is an example of the @code{PREFIX}, @code{TAG}, and @code{MARKER}
keywords:

@float Example, PREFIX, MARKER, and TAG Example
@example
AGGREGATE operator STRUCTURE MARKER doowop_ PREFIX beebop_ TAG shoo;
    flink ADDRESS;
    blink WORD;
END;
@end example
@cindex ADDRESS keyword
@cindex ADDRESS example
@cindex AGGREGATE keyword
@cindex AGGREGATE declaration
@cindex AGGREGATE example
@cindex END keyword
@cindex MARKER example
@cindex PREFIX example
@cindex STRUCTURE example
@cindex TAG example

