@node RADIX Keyword
@subsubsection RADIX Keyword
The RADIX keyword can be used to indicate how a constant value should
be written out to the output file.  It can have one of three possible values.

@itemize @bullet
@item @strong{@code{DEC}} --- for Decimal
@item @strong{@code{OCT}} --- for Octal 
@item @strong{@code{DEC}} --- for Hexadecimal
@end itemize
@cindex Decimal notation
@cindex Hexadecimal notation
@cindex Octal notation

For example:
@example
CONSTANT MyConst EQUALS 42 RADIX HEX;
@end example
@cindex CONSTANT example
@cindex EQUALS example

will generate the following C code header file:

@example
#define MyConst 0x2a
@end example

@quotation Note
When a @code{BITMASK} has the optional @code{MASK} keyword, constant values are
generated consistent with the @code{RADIX HEX} keyword.
@end quotation
@cindex MASK keyword

@node Alignment Keywords
@subsubsection Alignment Keywords
@cindex Alignment
@cindex Alignment keywords
@cindex ALIGN keyword
Both the @code{ALIGN} and @code{BASEALIGN} keywords can ensure that items are
properly aligned.  The @code{BASEALIGN} keyword takes an argument, which
specifies the alignment, whereas the @code{ALIGN} keyword uses the natural
alignment of the item.
@cindex BASEALIGN keyword

@itemize @bullet
@item If the @code{ALIGN} keyword is included in the definition of an
aggregate, every member will be aligned.  Both @code{i1} and @code{i2} will be
aligned.
@example
AGGREGATE MyStruct STRUCTURE ALIGN;
    c1 CHARACTER;
    i1 LONGWORD;
    c2 CHARACTER;
    i2 LONGWORD;
END;
@end example
@cindex AGGREGATE example
@cindex AGGREGATE member
@cindex Alignment example
@cindex ALIGN example
@cindex CHARACTER example
@cindex END keyword

@item If the @code{ALIGN} keyword is included in the definition of a member of
an aggregate, this member will be aligned, even if the @code{AGGREGATE} itself
does not have the @code{ALIGN} attribute.  @code{i2} will be aligned whereas
@code{i1} will not be aligned.
@example
AGGREGATE MyStruct STRUCTURE NOALIGN;
    c CHARACTER;
    i1 LONGWORD;
    i2 LONGWORD ALIGN;
END;
@end example
@cindex AGGREGATE example
@cindex Alignment example
@cindex ALIGN example
@cindex CHARACTER example
@cindex END keyword

@item If the @code{NOALIGN} keyword is included in the definition of a member
of an aggregate, no action will be taken to ensure that this member will be
aligned, even if the @code{AGGREGATE} has the @code{ALIGN} attribute.
@code{i2} will be aligned, @code{i1} will not be aligned.
@example
AGGREGATE MyStruct STRUCTURE ALIGN;
    c CHARACTER;
    i1 LONGWORD NOALIGN;
    i2 LONGWORD;
END;
@end example
@cindex AGGREGATE example
@cindex Alignment example
@cindex ALIGN example
@cindex CHARACTER example
@cindex END keyword

@item If the @code{NOALIGN} keyword is included in the definition of an
aggregate, no action will be taken to ensure that any member of this aggregate
will be aligned.  Neither @code{i2} nor @code{i1} will be aligned.
@example
AGGREGATE MyStruct STRUCTURE NOALIGN;
    c CHARACTER;
    i1 LONGWORD;
    i2 LONGWORD;
END;
@end example
@cindex AGGREGATE example
@cindex Alignment example
@cindex CHARACTER example
@cindex END keyword

@item If the @code{BASEALIGN} keyword is included in the definition of a member
of an aggregate, this member will be aligned according to the given alignment.
In this case, @code{i2} will have an offset of 256 (@math{2@sup{8}}),
@example
AGGREGATE MyStruct STRUCTURE NOALIGN;
    c CHARACTER;
    i1 LONGWORD;
    i2 LONGWORD BASEALIGN(8);
END;
@end example
@cindex AGGREGATE example
@cindex Alignment example
@cindex BASEALIGN example
@cindex CHARACTER example
@cindex END keyword

@item If the @code{BASEALIGN} keyword is included in the definition of an
aggregate or an item, the aggregate or item itself will be padded, so that in
an array of elements of this aggregate or item type, all elements will be
aligned according to the given alignment.  The syntax is as follows:
@example
AGGREGATE MyStruct STRUCTURE BASEALIGN (2);
    c CHARACTER;
    i1 LONGWORD;
    i2 LONGWORD;
END;
@end example
@end itemize
@cindex AGGREGATE example
@cindex Alignment example
@cindex BASEALIGN example
@cindex CHARACTER example
@cindex END keyword

The size of the aggregate will be a multiple of 4 (@math{2@sum{2}}), in this
case 12, and neither @code{i1} nor @code{i2} will be aligned.  In the following
example, the item will have a size of 8 (@math{2@sup{3}}).

@example
ITEM MyItem LONGWORD UNSIGNED BASEALIGN (3);
@end example
@cindex UNSIGNED example
@cindex BASEALIGN example
@cindex ITEM example

@node Storage Class Keywords
@subsubsection Storage Class Keywords
@cindex Storage classes

Storage class refers to the way in which the target language compiler allocates
storage for scalar items and aggregates.  In general, declarations produce a
template describing data for which the compiler allocates storage dynamically
at run time, rather than at compile time.  This type of storage is the default
and is specified using the @code{BASED} option in some languages, although the
default storage class option is language-dependent.  The back end can
generate the @code{BASED} storage class option, which has the following
syntax:
@cindex Default storage class
@cindex Scalar items

@example
BASED (pointer-name)
@end example
@cindex BASED keyword
@cindex BASED storage class

In languages that support the construct, you can use the @code{BASED}
pointer-name option on an @code{AGGREGATE} declaration to bind a named pointer
to that aggregate.  In all target languages, the aggregate resulting from such
a declaration has the default storage class (@code{BASED}).
@cindex AGGREGATE keyword
@cindex AGGREGATE declaration
@cindex Default storage class
@cindex Storage classes

A subaggregate always acquires the storage class of the aggregate to which it
belongs.  The default storage class associated with any declaration is
language-dependent.  You can override the default storage class by specifying
either of the following storage classes:
@cindex Default storage class
@cindex Storage classes
@cindex Subaggregate declaration

@itemize @bullet
@item @strong{Common storage} is allocated in an external program section
(Psect) with the OVR option and is shared by all routines that reference it.
You declare data in common storage by using the @code{COMMON} option on an
@code{AGGREGATE} or @code{ITEM} declaration.
@cindex AGGREGATE keyword
@cindex AGGREGATE declaration
@cindex COMMON keyword
@cindex COMMON storage class
@cindex ITEM keyword
@cindex ITEM declaration
@cindex OVR option
@cindex Psect

@item @strong{Global storage} represents data in a global storage location
whose value is defined elsewhere.  You declare global data by using the
@code{GLOBAL} option on an @code{AGGREGATE} or @code{ITEM} declaration.
@cindex AGGREGATE keyword
@cindex AGGREGATE declaration
@cindex GLOBAL storage class
@cindex ITEM keyword
@cindex ITEM declaration

@item @strong{TYPEDEF} behaves like a storage class.  In C/C++, examples of
storage classes are @code{static}, @code{globaldef/ref}, @code{extern}, etc.
Syntactically, you can replace a @code{static} in any declaration with
@code{typedef} and have it compiled.  Storage classes (including
@code{TYPEDEF}) are mutually exclusive in an OpenSDL declaration.
@cindex OpenSDL declarations
@cindex Storage classes
@cindex TYPEDEF storage class

Example of C/C++ type definition:
@example
typedef struct @{int32_t jg_l_i1; int32_t j_l_i2;@} MyStruct;
static MyStruct foo;
@end example
is equivalent to:
@example
static struct @{int32_t jg_l_i1; int32_t jg_l_i2;@} foo;
@end example
or:
@example
static struct MyStruct @{int32_t jg_l_i1; int32_t jg_l_i2;@} foo;
@end example
or:
@example
struct MyStruct @{int32_t jg_l_i1; int32_t jg_l_i2;@};
static struct MyStruct foo;
@end example
@end itemize

If @code{COMMON} and @code{GLOBAL} appear together in a declaration, a
@code{SDL_DUPCONATT} (duplicate or conflicting attributes) error is given.  The
@code{COMMON}, @code{GLOBAL} and @code{TYPEDEF} storage classes are mutually
exclusive.
@cindex COMMON keyword
@cindex COMMON declaration
@cindex TYPEDEF keyword
@cindex TYPEDEF declaration

@subsubsection OpenSDL Storage Classes and Typedef Syntax
Explicit OpenSDL Storage classes are @code{COMMON} and @code{GLOBAL}.  To
maintain orthogonal syntax, @code{TYPEDEF} is permitted wherever @code{COMMON}
and @code{GLOBAL} are permitted.
@cindex COMMON storage class
@cindex Storage classes
@cindex TYPEDEF storage class

The Storage class definition in OpenSDL is included as an option on an
@code{ITEM} or @code{AGGREGATE} declaration.  This means that an
@code{AGGREGATE TYPEDEF} for the preceding example would be:
@cindex AGGREGATE keyword
@cindex AGGREGATE declaration
@cindex ITEM keyword
@cindex ITEM declaration
@cindex Storage classes
@cindex TYPEDEF keyword


@example
AGGREGATE MyStruct STRUCTURE TYPEDEF PREFIX jg_;
    i1 LONGWORD;
    i2 LONGWORD;
END;
@end example
@cindex AGGREGATE example
@cindex END keyword
@cindex PREFIX example

@subsubsection Data Types
In most cases it is possible to refer to a user-defined Data Type where a
standard built-in OpenSDL Data Type (BYTE, LONGWORD etc.) can be referenced.
Reference to the type MyStruct defined in the preceding example is made as
follows:
@cindex BYTE keyword
@cindex Data type, user defined
@cindex Data type, TYPEDEF
@cindex TYPEDEF keyword

@example
ITEM foo MyStruct;
@end example
@cindex ITEM example

@page

@node DIMENSION Keyword
@subsubsection DIMENSION Keyword
@cindex DIMENSION keyword

You can apply a dimension to @code{AGGREGATE} (as well as members of aggregates
and subaggregates) and @code{ITEM} declarations, which means that you can
define an array of structures, a structure that contains one or more arrays, or
an array of structures each of which contains one or more arrays.  The
@code{DIMENSION} option is valid when specified with any of the data types
described in @ref{Data Type Keywords} and has the following syntax:
@cindex AGGREGATE keyword
@cindex AGGREGATE declaration
@cindex AGGREGATE member
@cindex Arrays
@cindex ITEM keyword
@cindex ITEM declaration
@cindex Subaggregate declaration

@example
DIMENSION [lbound:]hbound
@end example

@strong{@code{lbound}}
@indentedblock
Is any valid OpenSDL expression giving the value of the lowest-numbered element
of the array.  If lbound is not specified, OpenSDL supplies a default
@code{lbound} of 1.
@end indentedblock

@strong{@code{hbound}}
@indentedblock
Is any valid OpenSDL expression giving the number of elements in the array, or,
if @code{lbound} is specified, the highest-numbered element.
@end indentedblock

The following is an example of the @code{DIMENSION} option specified on an
@code{AGGREGATE} declaration:
@cindex AGGREGATE keyword

@example
AGGREGATE array_info STRUCTURE;
    bound STRUCTURE DIMENSION 8;
        lower LONGWORD;
        upper LONGWORD;
        multiplier LONGWORD;
        constant_lower BITFIELD LENGTH 1;
        constant_upper BITFIELD LENGTH 1;
        constant_multiplier BITFIELD LENGTH 1;
        reserved BITFIELD LENGTH 13;
    END bound;
END array_info;
@end example
@cindex AGGREGATE example
@cindex AGGREGATE member
@cindex BITFIELD example
@cindex CONSTANT example
@cindex DIMENSION example
@cindex END keyword
@cindex LENGTH example

The subaggregate bound has eight elements.  Each element consists of the members
upper, lower, multiplier, and so on.  Because bound is an array, each of its
members (upper, lower, multiplier, and so on) can also be considered an array
of eight elements.  When you specify a single value after the @code{DIMENSION}
keyword, as in the previous example, the specified back end assumes that the
value represents the high bound value and supplies a default low bound value of
one.  You can override this default by specifying both a low bound and a high
bound value as follows:
@cindex Subaggregate declaration

@example
ITEM node_pointers DIMENSION 0:255 ADDRESS;
@end example
@cindex ADDRESS example
@cindex DIMENSION example
@cindex ITEM example

This declaration results in a declaration of the array node_pointers, whose low
bound is 0 and whose high bound is 255.  Only one dimension can be specified for
an @code{AGGREGATE} or @code{ITEM} declaration.  This restriction ensures that
there is no interlanguage conflict in an array declaration.
@cindex AGGREGATE keyword
@cindex ITEM keyword

You can see how OpenSDL translates the @code{DIMENSION} option for each output
language by processing the OpenSDL source file
@file{/usr/lib/OpenSDL/examples/example.sdl}.
@cindex DIMENSION option
@cindex DIMENSION example

@page

@node Data Type Keywords
@subsection Data Type Keywords

Data type keywords specify the data types of scalar objects, which can be
declared as members of aggregates or as individual items.  Data type keywords
are also used to describe the data types of parameters, as well as the return
value of an @code{ENTRY}.  They can also be used in an @code{AGGREGATE}
declaration to generate an implicit union.  The data type declaration also
specifies, either implicitly or explicitly, the size of a member.
@cindex AGGREGATE keyword
@cindex AGGREGATE member
@cindex Implicit union declaration
@cindex Data types
@cindex ENTRY keyword

The following sections describe the data types and the keywords you use to
specify them.

@subsubsection Pointer Data Types
The keywords @code{ADDRESS}, @code{POINTER}, @code{POINTER_LONG},
@code{POINTER_QUAD}, @code{POINTER_HW}, and @code{HARDWARE_ADDRESS} specify a
data type that is an address, or pointer.  The @code{ADDRESS} data type has the
following syntax:
@cindex ADDRESS keyword
@cindex ADDRESS data type
@cindex ADDRESS declaration
@cindex Data type, ADDRESS
@cindex POINTER keyword
@cindex POINTER data type
@cindex POINTER declaration
@cindex Data type, POINTER
@cindex POINTER_LONG keyword
