@node Local Comments
@section Local Comments
@cindex Comments
@cindex Local comments
@cindex Not output comments

A comment that is local to the OpenSDL source file is not written to the output
file.  Local comments begin with the left brace (@code{@{}) and extend to the
end of the line.  They can appear anywhere within the source file (not
necessarily within a module) where white space (a space, tab, or carriage
return) is allowed.  The following is an example of a local comment:

@example
@{ Assigning the value 255 to #max_args.
@end example

@node Output Comments
@section Output Comments
@cindex Comments
@cindex Output Comments

There are two types of output comments, Line Comments and Block Comments.

@subsection Line Comments
@cindex Line comments

Line comments appearing on lines by themselves are typically written to the
output file as separate comment lines.  Line comments appearing at the end of a
line are output at the end of the corresponding target source line, if
possible.

Line comments begin with a slash and an asterisk (@code{/*}) and terminate at
the end of the current line.  They can appear in the following contexts:
@itemize @bullet
@item Outside @code{MODULE} declarations
@cindex MODULE declaration

@item At the end of a line containing a declaration, that is, following the 
semicolon terminator(@code{;})

@item On lines by themselves between member, @code{CONSTANT}, @code{ENTRY},
@code{ITEM}, and @code{AGGREGATE} declarations
@cindex AGGREGATE keyword
@cindex AGGREGATE member
@cindex ENTRY keyword
@cindex ITEM keyword

@item Between declarations with in an aggregate

@item Following individual constant names with in a comma-delimited list of
@code{CONSTANT} declarations
@end itemize
@cindex CONSTANT keyword
@cindex CONSTANT declaration

The following is an example of a line comment:

@example
/* Get Job/Process Information System Service.
@end example
@cindex Output comments example
@cindex Line comments example

@subsection Block Comments
@cindex Block comments

Block comments are those that appear as a large multi-line comment and are
written to the output file as multiple comment lines.

Block comments begin with a slash and a plus sign (@code{/+}) and end with a
slash and a minus sign (@code{/-}).  Within these begin and end comments, lines
beginning with a double slash (@code{//}) will be prefixed with a middle
comment (if the target language supports it).  These comments can appear
anywhere Output Comments can appear.

The following are two examples of a block comments:

@example
/+
// Get Job/Process Information System Service.
/-

/+
 Copyright 2018.
/-
@end example
@cindex Output comments example
@cindex Block comments example

@node INCLUDE Statement
@section INCLUDE Statement
@cindex INCLUDE statement

The @code{INCLUDE} statement specifies that the contents of an external file
are to be incorporated in the OpenSDL input file directly following the
@code{INCLUDE} statement.  The @code{INCLUDE} statement has the following
syntax:

@example
INCLUDE "file-spec";
@end example
@cindex INCLUDE example

@strong{@code{"file-spec"}}
@indentedblock
Is any valid file specification enclosed in quotation marks (" ").  An
@code{INCLUDE} statement cannot appear embedded within an @code{AGGREGATE}
declaration, but can appear anywhere else within the module.  If a directory
is not included in the file specification, the current default directory is
used.
@end indentedblock
@cindex AGGREGATE keyword
@cindex INCLUDE statement

When OpenSDL encounters an @code{INCLUDE} statement, it stops reading from the
current file and reads the statements in the included file.  When it reaches
the end of the included file, OpenSDL resumes translation with the source
statement immediately following the @code{INCLUDE} statement.

@node Conditional OpenSDL Compilation
@section Conditional OpenSDL Compilation
@cindex Conditional compilation

@subsection Conditional OpenSDL Compilation using the IFLANGUAGE statement

This feature allows a section of OpenSDL source code to be conditionally
compiled, depending on whether output is being generated for a particular
language or not.

The syntax for conditional compilation has the format:

@example
IFLANGUAGE language-name [ language-name ...  ] ;
    .
    .
    .
[ELSE ;
    .
    .
    .
]
END_IFLANGUAGE [ language-name [ language-name ...  ] ] ;
@end example
@cindex IFLANGUAGE statement
@cindex END_IFLANGUAGE statement
@cindex ELSE statemment

Note the following:

@itemize @bullet
@item The three keywords may appear wherever a statement is valid.

@item Conditional compilation statements may not be nested.

@item The list of language-names on the @code{END_IFLANGUAGE} is optional, but
if it is included, it must match the list on the @code{IFLANGUAGE} statement.
The languages need not necessarily appear in the same order.
@cindex IFLANGUAGE statement
@cindex END_IFLANGUAGE statement

@item Language names may not be abbreviated.

@item The validity of language names is not checked.  This is in keeping with
the philosophy of OpenSDL that new back ends may be added without changes to
the front end.

@item A comment on the same line as the @code{IFLANGUAGE} statement is only
output for languages which satisfy the condition.  A comment on the same line
as the @code{END_IFLANGUAGE} statement is always output, as this is considered
to be outside the body of the conditional.
@cindex IFLANGUAGE statement
@cindex END_IFLANGUAGE statement
@end itemize

In the following example, OpenSDL generates a translation of the ITEM statement
if output is being generated for Pascal, Ada, or FORTRAN.  For other languages,
OpenSDL does not generate a translation of the ITEM statement.

@example
IFLANGUAGE PASCAL ADA FORTRAN;
    ITEM foo LONGWORD;
END_IFLANGUAGE PASCAL ADA FORTRAN;
@end example
@cindex END_IFLANGUAGE example
@cindex IFLANGUAGE example
@cindex ITEM example

@page

@subsection Conditional OpenSDL Compilation using the IFSYMBOL statement

This feature allows a section of OpenSDL source code to be conditionally
compiled, depending on symbols specified with the command line qualifier
@command{--symbol}.  The syntax for conditional compilation has the format:
@cindex Command line qualifiers

@example
IFSYMBOL symbol-name ;
    .
    .
    .
[ ELSE_IFSYMBOL symbol-name ;
    .
    .
    .
]
[ELSE ;
    .
    .
    .
]
END_IFSYMBOL ;
@end example
@cindex IFSYMBOL statement
@cindex ELSE_IFSYMBOL statement
@cindex END_IFSYMBOL statement
@cindex ELSE statemment

Note the following:
@itemize @bullet
@item The four keywords may appear wherever a statement is valid.
@item Conditional compilation statements may not be nested.
@item A comment on the same line as the @code{IFSYMBOL} statement is only
output if this symbol is specified on the command line.  A comment on the same
line as the @code{END_IFSYMBOL} statement is always output, as this is
considered to be outside the body of the conditional.
@cindex END_IFSYMBOL statement
@end itemize

With the following example:
@cindex Conditional compilation example

@float Example, Conditional Compilation Example
@example
IFSYMBOL s1;
    <sdl code 1>
END_IFSYMBOL;
IFSYMBOL s2;
    <sdl code 2>
ELSE_IFSYMBOL s3;
    <sdl code 3>
ELSE;
    <sdl code 4>
END_IFSYMBOL;
@end example
@caption{Conditional Compilation Example}
@end float
