@node DECLARE Statement
@section DECLARE Statement
@cindex DECLARE statement

The @code{DECLARE} statement allows you to declare a data item of a type that
you define, which may be unknown in the current OpenSDL compilation.  When you
use @code{DECLARE}, the type is made known when the target language source is
compiled.

The @code{DECLARE} statement uses the @code{SIZEOF} clause to allow you to
specify the size of the user-defined data type being declared.  The parameter
you specify in the @code{SIZEOF} clause may be a built-in OpenSDL data type, a
user-defined type defined in the current OpenSDL compilation, or an expression.
@cindex Data type, user defined
@cindex DECLARE SIZEOF clause

The @code{DECLARE} statement has the following syntax:

@example
DECLARE user-type SIZEOF @{ data-type @}     [ PREFIX prefix-string ]
                         @{ user-type @}     [ TAG tag-string ]
                         @{ ( expression ) @}
@end example

@strong{@code{user-type}}
@indentedblock
Represents the unknown data type name you wish to declare.
@end indentedblock

@strong{@code{SIZEOF}}
@indentedblock
A clause that must be appended to user-type.  The @code{SIZEOF} clause may be
specified in several ways, as shown, to indicate the size of the user-defined
type being declared.
@end indentedblock

@strong{@code{data-type}}
@indentedblock
Represents either a built-in OpenSDL data type, a user-defined type that is
known at OpenSDL compile time, or a data type that has been sized by a previous
@code{SIZEOF} clause.
@end indentedblock

@strong{@code{user-type}}
@indentedblock
Represents a user-defined data type.
@end indentedblock

@strong{@code{( expression )}}
@indentedblock
Represents an expression.  If specified, the expression must specify the number
of bytes to be reserved for this data type.  If the data type is dimensioned,
the @code{SIZEOF} clause must specify the size of a single element.  When you
specify an expression, always enclose it in parentheses, as shown in this
syntax.
@end indentedblock

Notes:
@enumerate
@item @code{DECLARE} identifies the size of the data type when included in an
@code{AGGREGATE} declaration.  (OpenSDL needs to know its equivalent predefined
type so that the correct default tag letter, if required, can be output.)
@cindex AGGREGATE keyword
@cindex Data type, user defined
@cindex DECLARE statement

@item You may declare a user-defined data type more than once (either
explicitly or implicitly), but any subsequent declaration must match the first.

@item The default tag letter for the unknown variable being sized is derived
from the type specified in the @code{SIZEOF} clause.  If you use an expression
in place of a data type to reserve a fixed number of bytes, the default tag
letter is @code{T}.  You may override the default tag by using an explicit TAG
option.
@cindex Data type, tag
@cindex TAG keyword

@item @code{SIZEOF} clauses cannot be nested.

@item You cannot qualify a reference to the name of a previously-declared
aggregate using the @code{SIZEOF} clause.
@cindex DECLARE SIZEOF clause

@item Although @code{DECLARE} statements and implicit @code{SIZEOF}
declarations appear in the output tree for use by the back ends, these do not
result in specific generated code.
@cindex DECLARE statement
@cindex DECLARE SIZEOF clause

@item Do not use the @code{SIZEOF} clause for data types that are aggregate
names.  Also, do not nest @code{SIZEOF} clauses where the syntax would
otherwise allow aggregate names.  For example, the following statements are
valid:

@example
DECLARE type SIZEOF ADDRESS (CHARACTER);
ITEM type ADDRESS (bar SIZEOF LONGWORD);
@end example
@cindex ADDRESS example
@cindex DECLARE example
@cindex DECLARE SIZEOF example
@cindex ITEM example

However, the following statement generates an error message:

@example
DECLARE type SIZEOF ADDRESS (bar SIZEOF LONGWORD);
@end example
@end enumerate

@subsubheading Examples

A database contains information on a number of forests in a region, each of
which contains a number of different types of trees.  The definition of the
tree structure is held in a different OpenSDL file from the other definitions.
When the second OpenSDL file is compiled, the composition of the tree structure
is unknown --- the definitions will only come together when the output files
are included in a compilation in the target language.  The following shows the
two OpenSDL files and the corresponding output in C/C++.
@cindex Output files

@strong{@file{tree1.sdl}}:
@example
AGGREGATE tree STRUCTURE TYPEDEF;
    flink ADDRESS (tree);
    blink ADDRESS (tree);
    height LONGWORD;
    age LONGWORD;
END;
@end example
@cindex ADDRESS keyword
@cindex ADDRESS example
@cindex AGGREGATE keyword
@cindex AGGREGATE example
@cindex END keyword

@strong{@file{tree2.sdl}}:
@example
DECLARE tree SIZEOF (16);
AGGREGATE forest STRUCTURE TYPEDEF;
    oak tree;
    ash tree;
    elm tree;
    conifers tree DIMENSION 6;
END;
ITEM tree_pointer ADDRESS (tree);
ITEM tree_storage tree DIMENSION 1000;
ITEM region forest DIMENSION 4; @{No SIZEOF, since forest defined here @}
@end example
@cindex ADDRESS keyword
@cindex ADDRESS example
@cindex AGGREGATE keyword
@cindex AGGREGATE example
@cindex DECLARE statement
@cindex DECLARE example
@cindex DECLARE SIZEOF example
@cindex DIMENSION example
@cindex END keyword
@cindex ITEM example
@cindex TYPEDEF example

@strong{@file{tree1.h}}:
@example
typedef struct _tree
@{
    _tree *flink;
    _tree *blink;
    long int height;
    long int age;
@} tree;
@end example

@strong{@file{tree2.h}}:
@example
typedef struct _forest
@{
    tree oak;
    tree ash;
    tree elm;
    tree conifers[6];
@} forest;
tree *tree_pointer;
tree tree_storage[1000];
forest region[4];
@end example

Note that the @code{SIZEOF} information is discarded by C, but is used in
offset calculations.

@node Declarations
@chapter OpenSDL Declarations
@cindex Declarations
@cindex OpenSDL declarations

This chapter describes the function and format of each of the following OpenSDL
declarations:
@itemize @bullet
@item @code{MODULE} declaration
@item @code{ITEM} declaration
@item @code{AGGREGATE} and subaggregate declarations
@item @code{CONSTANT} declaration
@item @code{ENTRY} declaration
@end itemize
@cindex AGGREGATE keyword
@cindex AGGREGATE declaration
@cindex CONSTANT keyword
@cindex CONSTANT declaration
@cindex ENTRY declaration
@cindex ITEM keyword
@cindex ITEM declaration
@cindex MODULE declaration
@cindex Subaggregate declaration

OpenSDL declarations are composed of the language elements described in
@ref{Elements}.  The output generated by each OpenSDL declaration depends on
which back end is used for the translation.
@cindex OpenSDL declarations

Online examples of output files for each language are available by processing
the OpenSDL source file @file{/usr/lib/OpenSDL/examples/example.sdl}.
@ref{Summaries} provides translation summaries for each output language.

@heading MODULE Declaration
@cindex MODULE declaration

The following sections describe the function and format of a @code{MODULE}
declaration.

@section MODULE Description
@cindex MODULE description

A @code{MODULE} declaration groups all related symbols and data structures.
All declarations (other than local symbol assignments and local and output
comments) must occur within a module, which is delimited by the @code{MODULE}
and @code{END_MODULE} keywords.  An OpenSDL source file may contain multiple
@code{MODULE} declarations, but modules may not be nested.  You must specify a
module name on the @code{MODULE} declaration; this name corresponds to the name
of a macro or module in a given output language.  (@ref{Names} describes the
syntax for names.) For example:
@cindex Comments
@cindex Local comments
@cindex Output comments
@cindex Line comments
@cindex Block comments
@cindex Data structures
@cindex END_MODULE keyword
@cindex Local symbols
@cindex Local variables
@cindex MODULE declaration

@example
MODULE _modef;
@end example
@cindex MODULE example

This declaration generates the beginning of the declaration for the macro or
module named @code{_modef}.

You can use the @code{IDENT} option on a @code{MODULE} declaration to pass a
version number or other information that must be enclosed in quotation marks
(" ") to the output file.  For example:
@cindex IDENT keyword
@cindex MODULE keyword

@example
MODULE params IDENT "V2.0";
@end example
@cindex IDENT example
@cindex MODULE example

You can optionally specify the module name on the @code{END_MODULE} statement;
this is particularly useful if you place more than one @code{MODULE}
declaration in the same OpenSDL source file.  The module name is case-sensitive
and must match exactly (in case) the name specified on the @code{MODULE}
declaration.
@cindex END_MODULE keyword
@cindex MODULE keyword

@page

@section MODULE Format
A MODULE declaration has the following syntax:

@example
MODULE module-name [ IDENT "ident-string" ];
    [ module-body ];
        .
        .
        .
END_MODULE [ module-name ];
@end example
@cindex END_MODULE keyword
@cindex IDENT keyword

@strong{@code{MODULE module-name}}
@indentedblock
Specifies any valid OpenSDL identifier you want to use to identify the module.
@end indentedblock
@cindex MODULE declaration

@strong{@code{[IDENT "ident-string"]}}
@indentedblock
Specifies any valid OpenSDL identifier, or a string of any characters, that
must be enclosed in quotation marks (" ") and that either further identifies
the module or is a version number.
@end indentedblock

@strong{@code{[module-body]}}
@indentedblock
Is one or more of the following:
@itemize @bullet
@item @code{ITEM} declaration
@item @code{AGGREGATE} declaration
@item @code{CONSTANT} declaration
@item @code{ENTRY} declaration
@item Local symbol assignment
@item Local or output comment
@item @code{INCLUDE} statement
@item @code{DECLARE} statement
@item @code{IFLANGUAGE} construct
@item @code{IFSYMBOL} construct
@item @code{LITERAL} construct
@end itemize
@end indentedblock
@cindex AGGREGATE keyword
@cindex AGGREGATE declaration
@cindex CONSTANT keyword
@cindex CONSTANT declaration
@cindex DECLARE statement
@cindex ENTRY declaration
@cindex ENTRY keyword
@cindex INCLUDE statement
@cindex IFLANGUAGE statement
@cindex IFSYMBOL statement
@cindex ITEM keyword
@cindex ITEM declaraion
@cindex Local symbols
@cindex Local comments

@strong{@code{END_MODULE [module-name]}}
@indentedblock
Marks the end of the @code{MODULE} declaration.  The module-name, if specified,
must match the name on the most recently specified @code{MODULE} declaration.
@end indentedblock
@cindex END_MODULE keyword

@page

@heading ITEM Declaration
@cindex ITEM declaraion

The following sections describe the function and format of an @code{ITEM}
declaration.

@section ITEM Description
An @code{ITEM} declaration defines scalar items and single-dimensional arrays
of scalar items that are not members of aggregates.  You must specify an item
name and data type on the @code{ITEM} declaration.  For example:
@cindex Scalar items

@example
ITEM block_list_id WORD;
@end example

This declaration specifies the scalar item @code{block_list_id} of data type
@code{WORD}.

@section ITEM Format

An @code{ITEM} declaration has the following syntax:

@example
ITEM item-name @{ data-type @}         [ COMMON ]
               @{ user-type sizeopt @} [ GLOBAL ]
                                     [ TYPEDEF ]

                                     [ BASEALIGN basealign-option ]

                                     [ DIMENSION [ lbound: ] hbound ]

                                     [ PREFIX prefix-string ]

                                     [ TAG tag-string ];
@end example

@strong{@code{ITEM item-name}}
@indentedblock
Specifies any valid OpenSDL name used to identify the item.
@end indentedblock

@strong{@code{data-type}}
@indentedblock
Is any valid OpenSDL data type (see @ref{Data Type Keywords}).
@end indentedblock

@strong{@code{user_type sizeopt}}
@indentedblock
Is a user-defined data type using the @code{DECLARE} statements @code{SIZEOF}
clause, shown and described in @ref{DECLARE Statement}.
@end indentedblock
@cindex DECLARE statement
@cindex DECLARE SIZEOF clause

@strong{@code{[ COMMON ]}@*}
@strong{@code{[ GLOBAL ]}@*}
@strong{@code{[ TYPEDEF ]}}
@indentedblock
Is the storage class of the item, if other than the default (@code{BASED})
storage class (see @ref{Storage Class Keywords}).
@end indentedblock
@cindex BASED storage class
@cindex COMMON storage class
@cindex Storage classes
@cindex TYPEDEF storage class

@strong{@code{[ BASEALIGN basealign-option ]}}
@indentedblock
@code{BASEALIGN} specifies the alignment of an @code{ITEM}.  basealign-option
is either an integer expression in parentheses or the name of a data type.
@code{BASEALIGN} aligns the item on a multiple of the value of the
basealign-option.
@end indentedblock
@cindex Alignment
@cindex Alignment keywords
@cindex BASEALIGN keyword

@strong{@code{[ DIMENSION [ lbound: ] hbound ]}}
@indentedblock
Specifies that the item is an array.  If a single value is specified, that value
indicates the number of elements in the array.  Otherwise, lbound and hbound
represent lower and upper bounds of the array, respectively (see
@ref{DIMENSION Keyword}).
@end indentedblock
@cindex DIMENSION keyword
@cindex DIMENSION declaration

@strong{@code{[ PREFIX prefix-string ]}}
@indentedblock
Specifies a user-defined prefix that becomes part of the identifier.  It can be
any valid OpenSDL name with 0 to 32 characters, may or may not be enclosed in
quotation marks (" ") and may be null (see @ref{PREFIX MARKER and TAG
Keywords}.
@end indentedblock
@cindex PREFIX keyword

@strong{@code{[ TAG tag-string ]}}
@indentedblock
Specifies the user-defined tag that follows the prefix used in forming the
identifier.  It can be any valid OpenSDL name with 0 to 32 alphanumeric
characters; the tag must be enclosed in quotation marks (" ") if it begins with
a numeric character (see @ref{PREFIX MARKER and TAG Keywords}.
@end indentedblock
@cindex TAG keyword

@heading AGGREGATE Declaration
@cindex AGGREGATE keyword
@cindex AGGREGATE declaration

The following sections describe the function and format of @code{AGGREGATE} and
subaggregate declarations.
@cindex Subaggregate declaration

@page

@node AGGREGATE Description
@section AGGREGATE Description
@cindex AGGREGATE keyword
@cindex AGGREGATE declaration

An @code{AGGREGATE} declaration defines nonscalar items and dimensional arrays
of nonscalar items.  An aggregate must contain at least one member declaration.
The body of an aggregate can also contain local symbol assignments,
@code{CONSTANT} declarations, and subaggregate declarations.
@cindex AGGREGATE member
@cindex CONSTANT declaration
@cindex Local symbols
@cindex Nonscalar data items
@cindex Subaggregate declaration

You must specify a valid aggregate name on the @code{AGGREGATE} declaration.
For example:

@example
AGGREGATE dcb STRUCTURE;
    type CHARACTER;
    size WORD;
    next ADDRESS;
END dcb;
@end example
@cindex ADDRESS example
@cindex AGGREGATE example
@cindex CHARACTER example
@cindex END keyword

You must terminate an @code{AGGREGATE} declaration with the @code{END}
statement.  You can optionally specify the aggregate name on the @code{END}
statement.  The aggregate name is case-sensitive and must match exactly (in
case) the name specified on the @code{AGGREGATE} declaration.

An aggregate that is the target of an @code{ADDRESS} declaration must have the
default (@code{BASED}) storage class.
@cindex ADDRESS keyword
@cindex ADDRESS declaration
@cindex BASED storage class
@cindex END keyword
@cindex Storage classes

@subsection Subaggregate Declaration

Subaggregates are declared using the keyword @code{STRUCTURE} or @code{UNION}.
For example:

@float Example, Subaggregate Example
@example
AGGREGATE tree_node STRUCTURE;
    opcode WORD;
    lang_bits UNION;
        pli_bits STRUCTURE;
            resolved BITFIELD;
            psv BITFIELD;
            mark1 BITFIELD;
            spare_bits BITFIELD LENGTH 5;
        END pli_bits;
        c_bits STRUCTURE;
            value_variable_size BITFIELD;
            psv BITFIELD;
            expanded BITFIELD;
            resolved BITFIELD;
            reduced BITFIELD;
            spare_bits BITFIELD LENGTH 3;
        END c_bits;
    END lang_bits;
END tree_node;
@end example
@caption{Subaggregate Example}
@end float
@cindex AGGREGATE example
@cindex BITFIELD example
@cindex UNION example
@cindex END keyword
@cindex LENGTH example
@cindex Subaggregate example

In this example, the structures @code{pli_bits} and @code{c_bits} are both
subaggregates of the @code{union lang_bits}.  Because @code{lang_bits} is a
@code{union}, @code{c_bits} and @code{pli_bits} occupy the same storage.

The @code{COMMON}, @code{GLOBAL}, @code{BASED pointer-name}, and @code{ORIGIN}
options are invalid for a subaggregate.  All other @code{AGGREGATE} options are
valid.
@cindex AGGREGATE keyword
@cindex BASED keyword
@cindex COMMON keyword
@cindex ORIGIN keyword
@cindex Subaggregate declaration

@subsection STRUCTURE Declaration

@code{STRUCTURE} declarations produce aggregate or subaggregate declarations
that are structures.  The members are not overlaid; each member has a unique
offset from the beginning of the structure, which means that members occupy
consecutive storage locations.
@cindex AGGREGATE member
@cindex Subaggregate declaration

The following shows the syntax of a first-level @code{STRUCTURE} declaration:

@example
AGGREGATE aggregate-name STRUCTURE [ options ];
@end example
@cindex AGGREGATE keyword

The following shows the syntax of a @code{STRUCTURE} declaration as an
aggregate member, that is, a subaggregate @code{STRUCTURE} declaration:
@cindex AGGREGATE member
@cindex Subaggregate declaration

@example
member-name STRUCTURE [ options ];
@end example

@subsection UNION Declaration

@code{UNION} declarations produce aggregate or subaggregate declarations that
are unions.  The first-level members are overlaid, which means that they occupy
the same storage location.
@cindex AGGREGATE member
@cindex UNION declaration
@cindex Subaggregate declaration

Each first-level member begins at the beginning of the union and, thus, has an
offset of zero.  A @code{UNION} declaration lets you represent the same storage
location using different names and different data types.

The following shows the syntax of a first-level @code{UNION} declaration:

@example
AGGREGATE aggregate-name UNION [ options ];
@end example
@cindex AGGREGATE keyword
@cindex UNION keyword

The following shows the syntax of a @code{UNION} declaration as an aggregate
member, that is, a subaggregate @code{UNION} declaration:
@cindex AGGREGATE member
@cindex UNION declaration
@cindex Subaggregate declaration

@example
member-name UNION [ options ]
@end example

@subsection Implicit Union Declarations

You may specify data types on an @code{AGGREGATE} declaration to cause the
@code{AGGREGATE} declaration to become an implicit union declaration.  An
implicit union declaration has these features:
@cindex AGGREGATE keyword
@cindex Implicit union declaration

@itemize @bullet
@item Gives OpenSDL the ability to detect subfield overflow without the need to 
define extraneous @code{STRUCTURE} and @code{UNION} declaration names.
@item Makes user-defined fill fields unnecessary.  This feature is most useful
for data structures containing substructures that are required to begin at
fixed offsets.
@end itemize
@cindex UNION data type
@cindex Data structures
@cindex Data type, UNION
@cindex Offsets

The following OpenSDL source code shows the syntax of an implicit union
(structure B defines the implicit union declaration):

@float Example, Implicit Union Example
@example
AGGREGATE A STRUCTURE;
    B STRUCTURE LONGWORD;
        bit_string1 BITFIELD LENGTH 1;
        bit_string2 BITFIELD LENGTH 4;
    END B;
    last_item WORD;
END A;
@end example
@caption{Implicit Union Example}
@end float
@cindex AGGREGATE example
@cindex BITFIELD example
@cindex END keyword
@cindex Implicit union example
@cindex LENGTH example

This implicit union declaration would be more cumbersome if represented as
shown in the following @code{STRUCTURE} subaggregate:

@example
AGGREGATE A STRUCTURE;
    X UNION ;
        B LONGWORD;
        Y STRUCTURE ;
            bit_string1 BITFIELD LENGTH 1;
            bit_string2 BITFIELD LENGTH 4;
        END Y;
    END X;
    last_item WORD;
END A;
@end example
@cindex AGGREGATE example
@cindex BITFIELD example
@cindex UNION example
@cindex END keyword
@cindex LENGTH example
@cindex Subaggregate example

In the previous example, the names @code{X} and @code{Y} become OpenSDL
generated filler names in the implicit union case.
@cindex Fillers

You do not have to define the union @code{X} and the structure @code{Y} if an
implicit union declaration is used.  By giving the structure @code{Y} a type,
OpenSDL creates a union of field @code{Y} with the specified type overlaid with
a structure containing the fields in @code{Y}.  In some language translations,
such as BLISS and MACRO, the OpenSDL-generated union and structure (@code{X}
and @code{Y} above) can be suppressed in the output because they are considered
extraneous fields.  In C, it is necessary to use the OpenSDL-generated union
and structure to generate the correct offsets within a structure.  Because the
union is of the length specified in the structure type, no filler is necessary
to ensure that subsequent fields (for example, last_item) are at the correct
offset.  If the fields of a structure extend past the size specified, OpenSDL
flags the overflow.  The C/C++ translation for the previous implicit union
declaration example is as follows:
@cindex Implicit union declaration
@cindex Offsets

@example
struct A
@{
    union B
    @{
        uint32_t bit_string1 : 1;
        uint32_t bit_string : 4;
    @};
    int16_t last_time;
@};
@end example
@cindex Implicit union example

The OpenSDL source file @file{/usr/lib/OpenSDL/examples/example.sdl} shows an
example of an implicit union declaration.

@subsection Implicit Union Declarations with the Optional @code{DIMENSION}
Keyword
@cindex Implicit union with DIMENSION keyword

The following is an example of an OpenSDL structure defined with a data type
and the @code{DIMENSION} keyword:
@cindex Implicit union declaration
@cindex DIMENSION keyword

@float Example, DIMENSION Example
@example
AGGREGATE fid STRUCTURE WORD DIMENSION 3;
    first WORD;
    second WORD;
    third WORD;
END fid;
@end example
@caption{DIMENSION Example}
@end float
@cindex AGGREGATE example
@cindex Implicit union example
@cindex DIMENSION example
@cindex END keyword

In the previous example, a single structure is overlaid by an array of elements
of the type specified by the structure type.

The fid structure is a three-word field that can be addressed as a single field
or by each individual word so that it is easily defined in OpenSDL as
represented above.  The following is the C/C++ translation for the OpenSDL
source code in the previous example:

@float Example, DIMENSION Output
@example
union fid[3]
@{
    int16_t first;
    int16_t second;
    int16_t third;
@};
@end example
@caption{DIMENSION Output}
@end float

The implicit union declaration allows structures to grow without the need to
modify any trailing fillers.  OpenSDL detects any overflow that may occur if
the structure grows past the size of its data type.  The size of the aggregate
(in bytes) is equal to the size of the data type (in bytes) multiplied by the
upper dimension (if any).  If the size of the aggregate is greater than the sum
of the size of all its members, OpenSDL still translates the declaration.
However, if the size of the members exceeds the size of the aggregate, OpenSDL
issues a message that has the following format:
@cindex AGGREGATE member
@cindex Implicit union declaration
@cindex Fillers

@code{%SDL-E-TOOMANYFIELDS, Structure fid has too many fields [Line ?]}
@cindex Implicit union declaration

@subsection Forcing Negative Offsets
@cindex Forcing negative offsets
@cindex Negative offsets
@cindex Offsets

The default origin of an aggregate is the beginning of the first aggregate
member.  You may specify the @code{ORIGIN} option on a level-1 @code{AGGREGATE}
declaration to indicate that the origin is located at the beginning of any
aggregate member.  The resulting declaration forces all aggregate members
declared before the specified origin to be located at negative offsets from the
origin.  For example:
@cindex AGGREGATE member

@float Example, ORIGIN Example
@example
AGGREGATE nodes STRUCTURE ORIGIN qflink;
    flink ADDRESS;
    blink ADDRESS;
    qflink ADDRESS;
    qblink ADDRESS;
END;
@end example
@caption{ORIGIN Example}
@end float
@cindex ADDRESS keyword
@cindex ADDRESS example
@cindex AGGREGATE keyword
@cindex AGGREGATE example
@cindex END keyword
@cindex ORIGIN example

This declaration defines the origin of the structure nodes to be at the member
@code{qflink}, so you may address @code{flink} and @code{blink} as negative
offsets from @code{qflink}.  Specifying an origin does not change the values of
the current bit and byte offset symbols (@code{^} and @code{:}).  These are
always calculated as being relative to the beginning of the aggregate.
@cindex AGGREGATE member
@cindex Bit offset symbol
@cindex Byte offset symbols
@cindex Offsets

@node Forcing Data Alignment
@subsection Forcing Data Alignment
@cindex Alignment
@cindex Data alignment
@cindex Forcing data alignment

OpenSDL forces all @code{AGGREGATE} and subaggregate declarations to begin on
byte boundaries.  Thus, if an aggregate or subaggregate ends with
@code{BITFIELD} declarations that do not end on byte boundaries, OpenSDL
ensures that the next aggregate begins on a byte boundary by supplying
@code{BITFIELD} declarations as fillers, if necessary.
@cindex AGGREGATE keyword
@cindex BITFIELD keyword
@cindex Fillers
@cindex Subaggregate declaration

When OpenSDL adds @code{BITFIELD} declarations, it determines the length
required and provides a unique name of the form @code{string_V_FILL_n}.  The
string is the prefix supplied in the @code{AGGREGATE} declaration, or the
aggregate name if no prefix was supplied.  Within an aggregate, n begins at 0
and is incremented for each filler required.
@cindex AGGREGATE keyword
@cindex BITFIELD keyword
@cindex Fillers

The subaggregate declarations shown in the following example declare filler
bitfields to force byte alignment at the end of each subaggregate; this
programming practice makes it unnecessary for OpenSDL to perform the alignment.
@cindex Alignment
@cindex Fillers
@cindex Subaggregate declaration

@float Example, Alignment Example
@example
AGGREGATE tree_node STRUCTURE;
    opcode WORD;
    lang_bits UNION;
        pli_bits STRUCTURE;
            resolved BITFIELD;
            psv BITFIELD;
            mark1 BITFIELD;
            spare_bits BITFIELD LENGTH 5;
        END pli_bits;
        c_bits STRUCTURE;
            value_variable_size BITFIELD;
            psv BITFIELD;
            expanded BITFIELD;
            resolved BITFIELD;
            reduced BITFIELD;
            spare_bits BITFIELD LENGTH 3;
        END c_bits;
    END lang_bits;
END tree_node;
@end example
@caption{Alignment Example}
@end float
@cindex AGGREGATE example
@cindex BITFIELD example
@cindex UNION example
@cindex END keyword
@cindex LENGTH example
@cindex Subaggregate example

The current bit offset is set at 0 at the beginning of each aggregate and is
incremented by the bit lengths of each structure member in the aggregate at
that level.  In the following example, OpenSDL forces the structure flags to be
aligned on a byte boundary.
@cindex AGGREGATE member
@cindex Alignment

@example
AGGREGATE dcb STRUCTURE PREFIX dcb_;
        .
        .
        .
    uflags STRUCTURE;
        context BITFIELD LENGTH 3;
        local BITFIELD;
    END uflags;
    flags STRUCTURE;
        extern BITFIELD;
        relo BITFIELD;
    END flags;
@end example
@cindex AGGREGATE example
@cindex BITFIELD example
@cindex END keyword
@cindex LENGTH example
@cindex PREFIX example

The C/C++ translation of the OpenSDL @code{AGGREGATE} declaration in the
previous example is as follows:
@cindex AGGREGATE keyword

@example
struct dcb_r_dcb
@{
    struct dcb_r_uflags
    @{
        uint8_t dcb_v_context : 3;
        uint8_t dcb_v_local : 1;
        uint8_t dcb_v_fill_0 : 4;
    @};
    struct dcb_r_flags
