@heading CONSTANT Declaration

The following sections describe the function and format of a @code{CONSTANT}
declaration.

@section CONSTANT Description
A @code{CONSTANT} declaration generates a list of one or more named constants
in the output file.  You may specify a valid constant name or names and the
constant values to be assigned to them.  For example:
@cindex CONSTANT keyword
@cindex CONSTANT declaration
@cindex CONSTANT description
@cindex Named constants

@example
CONSTANT block_node_size EQUALS 24;

CONSTANT Strcon EQUALS STRING "This is a string constant" PREFIX Jg_;
@end example
@cindex CONSTANT example
@cindex EQUALS example
@cindex EQUALS STRING example
@cindex PREFIX example

The first declaration creates the named constant @code{block_node_size} and
assigns it the value 24.  The second declaration creates the named string
constant @code{Jg_K_Strcon} and assigns it the specified value.
@cindex Named constants

The values of both declared constants (except string constants) and local
symbols may be used in OpenSDL expressions.  However, there is an important
difference between declared constants and local symbols: declared constants are
translated directly to the output file, whereas local symbols are not passed
directly to the output file.  For example, you can define the local symbol
@code{#block_size} as follows:
@cindex Local symbols

@example
#block_size = 24;
@end example
@cindex Expressions

A subsequent @code{CONSTANT} declaration may refer to @code{#block_size} and
use the value 24, as follows:

@example
CONSTANT block_node_size EQUALS #block_size;
@end example
@cindex CONSTANT example
@cindex EQUALS example

@code{CONSTANT} declarations (except string constants) can also be specified in
a comma-delimited list, as follows:
@cindex CONSTANT declaration
@cindex EQUALS example
@cindex EQUALS keyword

@example
CONSTANT
    xyz EQUALS 10,
    alpha EQUALS 0,
    noname EQUALS 63;
@end example

To specify related constants with the same or incremental values, use a
@code{CONSTANT} declaration with the @code{INCREMENT} option.  In this form,
the @code{EQUALS} expression gives the value to be assigned to the first named
constant; values for subsequent constants are derived by incrementing the first
value by the specified increment and assigning the result to the next name in
the list.  For example:

@example
CONSTANT (
    bits,
    bytes,
    words,
    longs,
    quads,
    octas
    ) EQUALS 0 INCREMENT 1 PREFIX ctx_;
@end example
@cindex CONSTANT example
@cindex EQUALS example
@cindex INCREMENT example
@cindex Named constant example
@cindex PREFIX example

When OpenSDL assigns incremental values, it loops until values are assigned to
all the names in a list.  If there is no @code{INCREMENT} clause, the increment
value is 0; thus, the same initial value is assigned to all the names.  If
names are omitted from a comma-delimited list, OpenSDL reserves the numbers
that would be assigned to names in those positions.  This lets you reserve
numeric values for later assignment of names.  For example:
@cindex INCREMENT keyword
@cindex Numeric values

@example
CONSTANT
    (bad_block,bad_data,,,,
     overlay,rewrite) EQUALS 0 INCREMENT 4;
@end example
@cindex CONSTANT keyword
@cindex EQUALS keyword
@cindex INCREMENT keyword

In the previous example, OpenSDL assigns the values 0 and 4 to the names
@code{bad_block} and @code{bad_data}, reserves the values 8, 12, and 16, and
assigns the values 20 and 24 to the names @code{overlay} and @code{rewrite},
respectively.

The @code{COUNTER} option saves the last assigned value in a specified local
symbol for subsequent use.  For example:
@cindex COUNTER option
@cindex Local symbols

@example
CONSTANT (pli,c,bliss,macro)
    EQUALS 4 INCREMENT 4 PREFIX lang_
    COUNTER #lang;

CONSTANT (basic,pascal,fortran)
    EQUALS #lang + 4 INCREMENT 4 PREFIX lang_;
@end example
@cindex Addition operator
@cindex COUNTER example
@cindex EQUALS example
@cindex INCREMENT example
@cindex PREFIX example

The following table shows the constant names produced by these two
declarations.

